California Top 20 Attractions

California is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the United States, and not just for its family-friendly theme parks that can keep you entertained for days on end. Like other states along the West Coast, California has gorgeous coastlines, national parks, waterfronts, and even deserts.

California comprises some of the major U.S. cities: Los Angeles, San Francisco, Sacramento, San Diego, etc. Some of the places worth visiting are Lake Tahoe, Disneyland, Big Sur and Napa Valley.

There are also iconic pieces of architecture worth a view and the chance to see a celebrity in Hollywood. Whether you are looking for nature, mainstream entertainment, or cultural and educational activities, California has something to offer everyone. So you don't have to try to pick which of the hundreds of attractions to visit, here are the top ten.

1: Yosemite National Park

  • Rate attraction:

  • View Map

This gorgeous wilderness rests along the Sierra Nevada mountains. Its granite cliffs and waterfalls are the kind of beauty that only exists along America's West Coast: immense, majestic, and breathtaking.

The land was so stunning that John Muir, the famous naturalist, worked tirelessly to preserve the Yosemite Valley and the surrounding land as a national park before national parks even existed.

With one visit to any spot in the park, it's easy to see what was so worth preserving. Now every generation can experience this pristine and magnificent land just as Muir did a century ago.

Address: Yosemite National Park, CA 95389

Website: www.nps.gov

As one of the most iconic sights to grace the world of sitcom… the Golden Gate Bridge is one stop you just can’t miss! It is a massive, towering red suspension bridge that links the San Francisco Bay to the Pacific Ocean.

It is also a California landmark. Tourists come from far and wide to ride on its smooth streets, and to look upon the bay from the bridge. As an actual, functional roadway, it may seem like there isn’t much to do here, but the bridge is just the beginning!

On either side of the Golden Gate Bridge lie two stops. Both are optimal picture and lookout vantage points to get great views of not just the bridge but the iconic, golden city as well.

There are typically several tourists and locals walking, biking, running, jogging, vlogging, and everything in between at these stops because of how great the view is from up there.

Be sure to make the most of your memories and stop at a landmark for some iconic shots in front of such an iconic stop.

Address: Golden Gate Bridge, San Francisco, CA 94129

Website: www.goldengatebridge.org

Of all the Disney theme parks in the World, this is the only one to have been directly supervised by Walt Disney himself during its construction. He envisioned it after visiting various theme parks around the world with his daughters.

Wanting to create something for parents and children alike, he designed this park, with such attractions as Adventureland, New Orleans Square, Frontier Land, and Fantasyland. Each area is meant to capture the imagination of all who visit it, by giving it that magical Disney touch.

Address: 1313 Disneyland Dr, Anaheim, CA 92802

Website: disneyland.disney.go.com

The cliffs and ridges of Big Sur, draped with redwoods and rising right out of the ocean, are an unparalleled beauty to behold. The population here is sparse, but the hiking trails and vistas keep people moving through on a regular basis.

The construction of Highway 1, which weaves along the edge of the mountains, opened up the previously inaccessible region to arts and tourism, attracting the likes of Jack Kerouac and Hunter S. Thompson to its rustic locale.

The views from the highway are stunning, with many scenic viewpoints along the way for you to stop off and enjoy the twinkling blue ocean below.

Address: Big Sur, CA 93920

Website: www.bigsurcalifornia.org

The Simpsons, Shrek, and Despicable Me are some of the most popular franchises on display here. There are also water shows and stunt shows that are performed live. Characters that wander the grounds greeting guests include Beetlejuice, the Blues Brothers, and Marilyn Monroe.

Hiking is a popular draw, though it is only permissible outside of the hot summer months. Sights can also be taken in by car or motorcycle. Overnight campers often discover that Death Valley's stargazing is second to none, due to its remote location and dark night skies.

They also come to see Shamu, the name of the park's first resident orca and the name under which all the current orcas still perform.

Its high altitude makes it an alpine paradise for skiers, snowmobilers, and other winter outdoor enthusiasts. In the summer months, hiking, biking, and water sports are the main attraction.

No matter how you choose to enjoy this mountain paradise, the vistas that surround you will make it a trip to remember.

Due to budget constraints, the buffalo were left behind once shooting was completed, and now the herd is generally comprised of 150 animals.

Visitors to Santa Catalina Island can enjoy a glass bottom tour boat that takes them around the shipwrecks and coral reefs that lie offshore. Parasailing and surfing are also popular choices.

Address: Santa Catalina Island, CA 90704

Motels and attractions dating back to the dawn of American automobile tourism can still be found, like Trees of Mystery featuring a giant statue of Paul Bunyan and his blue ox, Babe.

The theme parks pale in comparison to the stately elegance of the surrounding forests, the natural beauty of which needs no augmentation.

The iconic Joshua Tree is the centerpiece of the Joshua Tree National Park, one of the most popular parks in California. The park encompasses an area split between the Mojave Desert and the Colorado Desert, established in 1994 for the preservation of the natural landscape and the native trees.

Joshua Tree National Park is among the top places to visit in California, attracting millions of people every year to the park grounds. Visitors can enjoy the beautiful scenery of the park filled with forests of Joshua Trees, unique rock formations, and untouched wilderness landscape.

Some of the favorite things to do in the park include hiking, rock climbing, stargazing, and camping. There are lots of trails set up around the park ranging in length and hiking difficulty, leading to points of interest such as the Hidden Valley, Arch Rock, the Giant Marbles, and the Barker Dam.

Head up to Key View by either hiking or driving for the best viewpoint in the park. You’ll have views of the San Andreas Fault and Coachella Valley – perfect for watching the sunrise or sunset.

Joshua Tree National Park has several visitor facilities - nine campgrounds with plumbing or the option for backcountry camping.

Address: 74485 National Park Drive, Twentynine Palms, CA 92277

Website: www.nps.gov

Heart Castle is an excellent example of the extravagant American lifestyle during the golden age of the early 20th-Century. The castle belonged to William Randolph Hearst, a media tycoon, and built by a famed woman architect, Julia Morgan.

The Hearst Corporation donated the house and all of its content to the State of California after his death. It was opened to the public in 1958 for a glimpse into his opulent lifestyle.

Hearst Castle was a home dwelling, developed to exhibit the vast art and furniture collections of Hearst, ultimately becoming a social venue for big parties. The castle includes original furnishing and art, seen throughout the main house, Casa Grande, and the cottages: Casa del Mar, Casa del Monte, and Casa del Sol.

Bus rides take visitors up the Enchanted Hill to the site of the castle for touring around the rooms and suites of the house or throughout the grounds. It features two large pools, a garden, and sits atop a hill for sights of the surrounding area. Visitors can take different tours for discovering the complex’s art, interiors, and more.

Hearst Castle is located near San Simeon, California, and visited by hundreds of thousands of people annually.

Address: 750 Hearst Castle Rd, San Simeon, CA 93452

Website: www.hearstcastle.org

The Channel Islands is an archipelago located just off the coast of California in the Pacific Ocean. Five of the eight islands make up the Channel Islands National Park, established in 1980 to preserve the natural scenery of the undeveloped islands.

The central hub of the national park is Santa Cruz Island, the largest of the Channel Islands. The park includes land and sea area, also designated as a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve for the abundant marine life and flora.

Visitors must take a ferry from the mainland to arrive at the islands (and travel between islands) to regulate tourism and maintain the island ecosystem. The main visitor center showcases exhibitions with information about the island and cultural history.

The Channel Islands National Park is popular for recreational activities and sightseeing. Some of the top things to do include diving, kayaking to explore the unique sea caves, hiking trails to scenic viewpoints, or relaxing on one of the many beaches. The park allows overnight camping.

The national park is open all year round, with autumn being the best time to catch whale sightings during migration. Other exciting marine life to see include dolphins and sea lions.

Address: Ventura, CA 93001

Website: www.nps.gov

In 1943, two parks, the Sequoia National Park and the Kings Canyon National Park, merged to create one large park, the Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks. The parks are open all year round and make for a perfect attraction for day trips or overnight stays in nature.

The diverse landscape of the parks includes a large area of the Sierra Nevada Mountain Range, among valleys, canyons, marble caves, and lots of glacial lakes. Some of the natural landmarks worth checking out include Mt. Whitney, one of the highest peaks in the US, San Joaquin Valley, Zumwalt Meadow, and the Roaring River Falls.

The park is well known for the giant sequoia trees located throughout the park.

Tourism is accessible for visitors coming to experience the scenic beauty of the park. Many people come for scenic drives through the mountains, the variety of hiking trails leading to the top destinations of the park or camping at the designated campsites. The park also includes a visitor center.

The area included within the park was initially occupied by Native Americans. Tour around the park, and you may discover archaeological sites serving as evidence of early human habitation.

Address: 47050 Generals Hwy, Three Rivers, CA 93271

Website: www.nps.gov

Whenever you’re in LA, be sure to look up – you might be able to see the iconic Hollywood Sign. Whether you’re viewing the sign from afar or take the hike up to see the letters up close in person, the Hollywood Sign is a must-see when visiting LA.

The Hollywood sign was created in 1923. Initially, the purpose of the sign was as an advertisement, but due to its popularity, the sign is now a mainstay landmark and pop culture icon for Hollywood. The Hollywood Sign Trust was established for the protection and maintenance of the letters.

The sign sits atop Mount Lee in the Hollywood Hills. The white letters measure at 45-ft tall and 350-ft long for all the letters combined. Throughout the years, the letters have gone lots of restoration efforts to maintain the current appearance.

Hiking up to the Hollywood sign is a frequent activity for visitors. Various hiking trails lead up to the top of the mountain – the most frequented route runs through Griffith Park, where you’ll have a great view overlooking LA.

The Hollywood Sign is a Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monument.

Address: Los Angeles, CA 90068

San Francisco is known for its steep hills – one of the architectural wonders to combat the steepness of the slopes for vehicles in a one-block stretch of Lombard Street. Lombard Street is considered the most crooked street in the world, complete with eight hairpin turns.

The one-way street leads downhill and recommended to drive 5mph. It’s an active street as part of US 101 highway and passes through the Russian Hill neighborhood. Due to popularity and slow driving speed at the block, the area frequently experiences traffic congestion. Current efforts are being made to regulate tourist driving to experience the steep, sharp turns.

Approximately two million people visit Lombard Street every year. The name derives after a street of the same name in Philadelphia. The block includes stairways on either side leading up to the top of the block, providing visitors a picturesque view of the curvy street and San Francisco.

Lombard Street is a stop along the cable car, which is one of the best ways to visit the road. You’ll be dropped off at the top of the block where you can walk down for photos while avoiding significant traffic of driving along the street.

Address: 1070 Lombard Street, San Francisco, CA 94109

Take a break from the upscale shopping and dining in LA to visit Venice Beach, one of the premier beaches LA most famous for its boardwalk. Venice beach stretches for miles, lined with lots of recreational areas and eclectic vibes along the boardwalk.

Millions of people come to Venice Beach every year, with the busiest time being during the Summer. Its nickname, ‘Muscle Beach,’ came from the outdoor gym equipment established along the beach. The beach includes several areas for enjoying sports such as basketball courts, skate parks, handball and tennis courts, and volleyball.

Visitors can rent bikes or electric scooters to ride along the boardwalk or the designated biking trails.

Surfing is very popular at Venice Beach, with the waters having the perfect conditions for all skill levels.

The highlight of Venice Beach is the boardwalk. Vendors line the boardwalk where you can find great souvenirs or check out some of the shops lining one side of it. The boardwalk is a mesh between the hipster culture of the locals and massive tourism. The atmosphere is perfect for people watching or enjoying the sights and sounds of the beach.

Address: Los Angeles, CA 90291

Monterey Bay Aquarium is one of the most visited attractions in Monterey, California. The aquarium is along the Monterey Bay, primarily exhibiting the marine life and ecosystems of the local bay for conservation efforts.

The aquarium receives more than two million visitors every year. The architecture features broad glass windows and an outdoor deck looking out towards the bay to create a seamless visual transition from the outdoors to the aquarium exhibits.

Monterey Bay Aquarium features a variety of permanent and temporary exhibitions. The aquarium is most known for successfully exhibiting a captured Great White Shark, an exhibit shut down due to resource consumption of maintaining the animal. 

The best exhibitions to check out in the aquarium are the Seawater systems, featuring over 35,000 animals of more than 500 species swimming in millions of gallons of water. The Open Sea Wing is also a notable exhibit, featuring one of the biggest aquarium windows in the world. Water conditions of each display are filtered depending on the natural habitats of the animals.

The Monterey Bay Aquarium serves an educational purpose, providing information and daily lectures about the sea creatures exhibited. There are hands-on exhibitions for kids, making it a very family-friendly destination to visit in California.

Address: 886 Cannery Row, Monterey, CA 93940

Website: www.montereybayaquarium.org

Before the Griffith Observatory was built, planetariums were thought of the be only accessible by scientists for research purposes. The observatory was built to counter the myth and make astrology available to everyone. It’s now one of the best things to do in LA for free.

The Griffith Observatory was built in 1935, located on Mount Hollywood within Griffith Park. There are hiking trails leading up to the observatory, or accessible via driving. It’s an excellent viewpoint overlooking the LA basin, Downtown Los Angeles, and the nearby Hollywood Sign.

Many people visit to enjoy the observatory grounds, being one of the best viewpoints in LA with beautiful scenery sounding the mountain. Come to take photos before heading inside to discover an entirely different world.

Inside the observatory are a variety of exhibitions and facilities. The exhibits showcase space and science themes – Foucault pendulum, a planetarium theatre, exhibitions of the evolution of telescopes, and the history of the universe. There are lots of interactive and live shows happening daily such as the Centered in the Universe show.

Visitors have a chance to look through the massive Zeiss Telescope, emerging from the observatory’s dome, for views of celestial bodies with clear skies.

Address: 2800 East Observatory Road, Los Angeles, CA 90027

Website: www.griffithobservatory.org

Santa Monica Pier is in Santa Monica, adjacent to Los Angeles. The pier starts off Colorado Avenue, transitioning into a hot spot for tourists and locals alike. The pier is a destination for fun, eating, and enjoying the sights.

One of the highlight features of the Santa Monica Pier is the towering Ferris wheel, located within the Pacific Park amusement park. Visit at nighttime to see the vibrant lights from the Ferris wheel. The amusement park is family-friendly with rides for all ages.

Santa Monica Pier features several other attractions, including the Santa Monica Pier Aquarium, a video game arcade, and frequently hosts outdoor concerts and movies during the Summer.

The pier is a popular place to find great restaurants – one of the favorite destinations is Bubba Gump Shrimp Company, thanks to scenes of Forest Gump shot here. In addition to the restaurants, some of the famous pier snacks include hand-dipped ice cream or try a hot dog on a stick.

Sightseeing, fishing, and exercising are a few of the recreational activities to do at the pier. There is seating along the pier or head down to the beach to relax with views of the pier in the background.

Address: 200 Santa Monica Pier, Santa Monica, CA 90401

Florida Top 20 Attractions

Florida is the perfect destination for those searching for sunshine, beaches, natural beauty, and culture. The Sunshine State is known for its beautiful weather that makes a trip to the beach perfect all year round.

Even if you don't want to go to the beach or visit a theme park, you can pick from a range of educational and entertaining attractions, such as visiting NASA centers, scuba diving, or even looking at forts that are centuries old.

Fishing, golfing, and hiking are just some of the outdoor adventures visitors to Florida enjoy. This list of the top 20 attractions in Florida can help you plan your perfect vacation.

This national park is the third largest in the country, after Yellowstone and Death Valley. The park was established in 1934 when development of the South Florida sealine threatened the vitality of the area. Nevada Top 10 Attractions

Nevada is largely a desert and semi-arid state but that has not detracted from its beauty. The state boasts several natural and man-made attractions that are a major tourist draw and the tourism industry is the largest business in Nevada.

Fifteen of the city's 25 hotels are located on the strip and the area is open 24-7. The Strip also has several golf courses, major malls, and restaurants.

From the Strip, tourists can see the fountains at the Bellagio, the Mirage's volcano and Caesars Palace with its Fall of Atlantic and Festival Fountains. The Strip has a vibrant nightlife and free trams operate from major hotels to the Strip all through the day.

Texas Top 20 Attractions

Texas is an amazing state filled with contrasts. From the beautiful beaches along the gulf coast to the historical Alamo in San Antonio or Dallas World Aquarium for the kids, there's always an abundance of activities and sites to keep visitors entertained.

Whether you're looking for the excitement of big city amenities or you want to relax and unwind in the history and culture of a slower pace of life, there's something for everyone in Texas.

So if you are planning for a vacation in Texas this Year, check out our list of top 20 "Must-See" attractions in Texas.

1: The Alamo

Photo Courtesy: Flickr/joenevill
  • Rate attraction:

    138

San Antonio is home to one of the most famous attractions in Texas, the Alamo. The Alamo is the site of a former Spanish mission, now converted into a museum experience. With over four million visitors every year, it's one of the most visited historic sites in the state – it's a UNESCO World Heritage Site and recognized as a National Historic Landmark.

The Alamo, or Alamo Mission in San Antonio, was built in the early 18th century. Spanish settlers used it for conducting religious missions for local Native Americans in the iconic Shrine of Texas Liberty chapel. The mission was later abandoned and regained prominence during the era of the Texas Revolution.

The abandoned site converted into a military fortress - it's most known for being the site of the Battle of the Alamo in 1836.

Today, the site is open to the public as a museum, allowing visitors to tour around the grounds – you can visit the chapel, the Long Barracks, and explore the museum. The museum holds an extensive collection of artifacts and recounts the history of the Alamo. It's an attraction that guests will truly never forget.

Address: 300 Alamo Plaza, San Antonio, TX 78205

Website: www.thealamo.org

In addition, visitors can cool down in the Palm Beach water park or chase thrills through the sky with the Moody Gardens zip line and ropes course.

When visiting the Fort Worth Stockyards you will have an opportunity to step into the West and get a glimpse of the culture that has made this area so popular.

From wooden corrals and brick walkways to the Stockyards championship rodeo and twice daily cattle drives, you'll be able to embrace the history of the Texas livestock industry.

You'll find a number of excellent dining options, ranging from fast food to Tex Mex, steakhouses, BBQ and more. After a bite to eat, you can take in some action at Billy Bob's Texas with its huge dance floor, indoor rodeo arena, arcade and general store.

There are several archaeological sites discovered in the park area – the sites show evidence of early inhabitants after finding caves with rock art and other artifacts.

Guadalupe Mountains National Park is a fun national park destination for visitors to enjoy the outdoors. It welcomes more than 150,000 visitors every year – some of the visitor facilities include a visitor center and a small museum.

Guide tours of the extensive caverns lead visitors 180-feet below the ground to discover the unique limestone formations.

Natural Bridge Caverns is just outside of San Antonio, named after a naturally formed bridge near the cavern entrance. The dark caves are illuminated with lights and feature massive limestone still being developed. The interior conditions of the caverns are wet and humid.

The caverns were discovered in 1960 and opened to the public as a tourist destination in 1964. Guided tours take groups of visitors through the underground routes of the cavern, reaching large open spaces – some rooms as large as a football field.

Along the tour, you'll learn lots of interesting information and history about the caverns and how they developed.

The museum presents lots of information and details about the tragedy.

The Sixth Floor Museum at Dealey Plaza opened in 1989, with the museum exhibition floor preserved since the 1960's – much of the space remains as it was after the day of the tragedy. Visitors can step into the past with the multimedia exhibition – it includes artifacts from the sniper and JFK, films about the event, photos, and other displays.

Audio guides are available to learn more details about each showcase and hear stories about the life and death of JFK.

The window where the shots came from remains open; it has a live webcam view looking down on the street. Before (or after) visiting the museum, you can check out the outdoor markings on the road of the exact spots where the shots occurred.

The USS Lexington is an award-winning ship for its service during commission. It played a significant role in World War II when the US Navy utilized it in the Pacific Ocean. The tour experience of the USS Lexington lets visitors see some of the notable rooms – Combat Information Center, the catapult room, the bridge, and the deck. Kemah Boardwalk hosts outdoor concerts and events throughout the year. Visitors can enjoy great music while hanging around the marina, which has the largest concentration of ships in the US.

The namesake features of the park are multiple dinosaur tracks left from millions of years ago around various locations around the river.

In addition to the tracks, there is also a museum located within the park.

Virginia Top 10 Attractions

With its location along the east coast, it is no surprise that Virginia hosts multiple great beaches. This state is also rich in history and was actually the English Crown's former dominion and the birthplace of multiple presidents.

That means that history buffs will find no shortage of tourist sites to transport them back in time. At the same time, beach lovers will find sandy shores and clear ocean water, shoppers will notice plenty of great stores, couples can find the chance for romance, and families can enjoy the outdoors or adventure parks.

You don't want to miss any of the top sites in Virginia so be sure to plan ahead to catch all of the historic, fun, or relaxing attractions.

Virginia Beach is the biggest city in the US state of Virginia. The place attracts millions of tourists every year and is a favorite vacation spot. The city offers a host of attractions to the visitors.

There are historic places, zoos and aquariums, and restaurants offering delicious haute cuisine, not to mention the sprawling beach on the South Atlantic and endless opportunities to indulge in all kinds of delightful and fun water activities.

The place also boasts of a thriving night life and there are special Virginia Beach Events which range from watersports and marathons and surfing competitions to live music and special evening concerts, etc.

This is a cemetery with a long and rich history, so it is well worth taking a guided tour when you visit. Make sure you also pay a visit to the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier and the Memorial Amphitheater to make your visit all the more memorable.

Arizona Top 10 Attractions

Arizona may have been the last of the 48 contiguous United States, but it offers plenty of options for visitors from near and far. The fame of the Grand Canyon draws in visitors, but the remaining natural features, museums, and family attractions encourage them to stay longer.

Georgia Top 10 Attractions

Southern comforts and Georgian charm go together like mashed potatoes and gravy. Things might move a little slower in Georgia, from the way people talk, walk, and cook; that doesn’t mean you’ll ever be bored, however. Georgia has lots of great things to do, outside of sampling the South’s best servings of soul food.

Visit Atlanta for some great city sights, as well as historic museums, zoos, and the world’s largest aquarium. If you’re looking to escape the urban setting for a while, go to the Cumberland Island reservation. They have wild horses that run free along the island’s coasts like a scene out of a romantic novel.

Georgia has an additional 47 state parks to explore, if you’re looking for more great places to view wildlife in its natural habitat. If you’re a history buff, you’ll find plenty of Civil War monuments, museums, and memorials. Here are the top 10 attractions in Georgia that you should include in your itinerary.

In addition to being able to see the wide variety of sea life and other creatures up close and personal, visitors can enjoy additional fun with exhibitions, events and even the 4D Theater.

The aquarium even hosts sleepovers so the little ones can enjoy a truly unique and memorable experience. There are plenty of great activities for visitors to look forward to making this an excellent choice for a great day out for the family.

At weekends you can pay a visit to the Farmer’s Market at the park and when you visit don’t forget to pay a visit to the famous Forsyth Park Fountain, which dates back to the 1850s.

Stone Mountain Park is also an ideal weekend getaway! It has golf, cable car rides, lodging, events, activities, and so much more to explore.

Hawaii Top 10 Attractions

Historically known for its sugar, pineapple, and whaling industries, Hawaii now economically depends on its U.S. military and tourism. Among the state's major assets is its natural and beautiful islands. Hawaii has eight primary islands: Hawaii, Oahu, Maui, Kauai, Molokai, Lanai, Niihau and Kahoolawe.

As far as tourism goes, Hawaii can keep every visitor happy. The Oahu Island is ideal for visitors who'd like to experience the beautiful islands but still remain within city conveniences. Hawaii also has options for the slow-paced tourists.

The several rainforests and waterfalls conjure up images of how the place would have look liked before the corporations arrived. Here are the top 10 attractions that you should not miss while you are in Hawaii.
